WEBVTT

00:03.895 --> 00:28.459
Another of the things that I thought would do well 
to discuss, and that you've been quite analytical

00:03.895 --> 00:28.459
of the situation all through the years, it just 
does help a whole lot to be bound together in

00:03.895 --> 00:28.459
association where we can learn not only the 
technological things, but learn how to get along

00:03.895 --> 00:28.459
together and with each other and to promote 
veterinary medicine for the benefit of the

00:03.895 --> 00:28.459
public. As an active person all through these 
years, I'm sure you espoused those views. Yes,

00:38.168 --> 00:57.810
that was

00:38.168 --> 00:57.810
one thing that we as board members were made to 
realize that that was our primary purpose was to

00:38.168 --> 00:57.810
benefit the public. And I appeared before the 
Sunset Commission at the last two or three years,

01:04.831 --> 01:11.739
three years ago, four years ago, I guess, when the 
veterinary board came under review. And that was

01:13.201 --> 01:22.491
the time that they proposed to put lay people on the 
veterinary board, examining board. And it was, to

01:24.433 --> 01:32.863
me, I think it was a mistake, but The legislature 
didn't seem to think so, and we did wind up with two

01:34.953 --> 01:39.579
members. But,

01:40.781 --> 02:00.088
you know, you have to have gone through a 
veterinary school to appreciate what we can do and

01:40.781 --> 02:00.088
the services that we do render. And what needs to be 
done. Yeah.

02:07.083 --> 02:18.538
It's just, I think the name of the game, as far as I'm 
concerned, is your client-veterinary

02:07.083 --> 02:18.538
relationship. That's just my feeling of it, and 
you can't get away from it. And I've seen so many

02:23.324 --> 02:36.702
newer graduates that, and I'm not setting myself 
up as an example, but so many newer graduates that

02:23.324 --> 02:36.702
the only thing they're looking for is the dollar. 
And it's, there's more to it than that.

02:45.564 --> 03:06.773
For, I can't help but notice some of their 
veterinarians as they've gone through the

02:45.564 --> 03:06.773
practice career, the ones who've just made an 
adequate living seem to be just as happy as many of

02:45.564 --> 03:06.773
those who have

02:45.564 --> 03:06.773
made a greater amount of money, so. Yeah. Well, 
very few, very few veterinarians ever got rich

03:11.045 --> 03:16.571
practicing veterinary medicine. A small 
percentage of them.

03:21.136 --> 03:24.620
The ones that got that made it on the... They made it 
on investments or some outside interest. On the

03:27.864 --> 03:28.705
side, yes. One of the things that I thought, since 
you've been around quite a while, is to discuss

03:35.913 --> 03:39.538
some of the acquaintances that you've known in 
veterinary medicine through the years. One of

03:40.440 --> 03:49.774
those grand people that we don't hear about and 
used to be secretary of the TVMA back in the early

03:40.440 --> 03:49.774
days was Dr. Marsteller. What are your 
recollections of Dr. Marsteller? Well, of

03:54.361 --> 03:59.108
course, he was dean when I went to school, say, at 
A&M. He was the dean. And I thought Dr. Marsteller

04:01.917 --> 04:05.340
was a very fine man. He was always receptive to any 
problems that I had. And

04:11.867 --> 04:22.938
I felt free to go in any time and just ask him 
anything that I wanted, and his door was always

04:11.867 --> 04:22.938
open. And he was a fine man. He was a very dedicated 
person.

04:31.178 --> 04:36.625
He was secretary back in the times when your dad was 
very active in the association. Did you ever hear

04:36.645 --> 04:40.389
your dad talk about him in the association? Oh, 
yeah. My dad and Dr. Marsteller were real close

04:41.230 --> 04:45.535
friends. And I first got to know him when my dad 
would go down for short courses at A&M during the

04:45.555 --> 04:53.305
summer. And I would go with him and got to know Dr. 
Marsteller.

05:01.435 --> 05:04.820
I'd stay over at the horse barn with Owen Garrigan. 
I don't know whether you ever knew Owen Garrigan or

05:04.860 --> 05:07.423
not. He was the greatest horseman that ever left 
A&M. And he had charge of all the horse barn, all the

05:12.430 --> 05:20.682
horses, and I'd stay over there with him a lot. And 
later on, when I went to school, I got me a job over

05:22.424 --> 05:29.434
there working for him. I didn't care about, of 
course, I needed the money, but he forgot more

05:31.844 --> 05:39.114
about horses than most people down there ever 
knew. He was a wonderful Scotchman, and he was a

05:39.554 --> 05:47.985
wonderful horseman.

05:48.005 --> 05:48.446
Wonderful. There's another man I thought I'd ask 
you about. During the World War I years, Dr. N.F.

05:57.778 --> 05:58.459
Williams was president for three years. You know, 
he spanned the war years. Did either you or your

06:03.252 --> 06:07.057
father have a personal acquaintance with him? No, 
I never had any acquaintance. I was never

06:09.820 --> 06:13.204
acquainted with Dr. Williams. Was he in vet 
school? He was in the ag department, wasn't he? No,

06:17.930 --> 06:21.074
he was a veterinarian in practice. I forget just 
where he practiced. But when the Two associations

06:25.810 --> 06:29.675
came together again after they'd been separated 
for four years. He seemed to be oil on troubled

06:30.656 --> 06:35.062
waters, and that's why I thought it had something 
to do with it. No, I've never heard his name

06:35.082 --> 06:36.844
mentioned. If I have, I've forgotten it. Okay. 
Another person who really worked hard stayed

06:39.948 --> 06:45.815
mostly in the laboratory, but he did get out 
around. I know I saw him in a lot of the veterinary

06:45.875 --> 06:48.819
meetings and so forth. Just to see him was Dr. 
Hubert Schmidt. Did you see much of him? I worked

06:53.669 --> 07:05.163
with Dr. Schmidt when I was in school, and he was 
working on X disease.

07:05.183 --> 07:06.504
Are you familiar with that? It's a toxic disease, 
is that correct? Yes. He did a lot of research on

07:08.727 --> 07:10.449
that.

